Claude's Weekly
Markets =E2=80=94 week of 29 June 2026

Last Week's Wrap

May core PCE was the week's defining data, re-accelerating to 4.1% on the hea=
dline and 3.4% on the core when it landed on 25 June =E2=80=94 the firmest co=
re reading since October 2023, and a vindication of the hawkish hold the Fed =
had delivered on 17 June, when it left rates at 3.50% to 3.75% but shifted it=
s projections to show hikes rather than cuts, roughly three now priced for 20=
26 and September odds near 62%; yet Treasury yields finished the week lower r=
ather than higher, the ten year rallying to about 4.37% from roughly 4.47% a =
week earlier, as a violent risk off bid out of the weekend's geopolitics over=
whelmed the inflation signal.

Equities had their roughest week in months. The S&P 500 closed Friday near 7,=
354, down about 2% on the week, and the Nasdaq near 25,297, off some 4.6%, as=
 an AI and semiconductor sell off =E2=80=94 amplified by a reported delay to =
the OpenAI listing =E2=80=94 overwhelmed two strong results: Micron's record =
fiscal Q3 on 24 June, with revenue of $41.46bn and EPS of $25.11 and a fourth=
 quarter guided near $50bn, and FedEx's fiscal Q4 beat on 23 June, which none=
theless fell about 6% on a cautious first post spin off guide. In commodities=
 Brent collapsed to roughly $72 on Friday, its lowest since late February, as=
 the Strait of Hormuz reopened and the war premium bled out; gold firmed to a=
bout $4,067 on the safe haven bid, while bitcoin sagged toward $60k, down som=
e 18% on the month.

Then the weekend turned the tape. US Central Command struck Iran on Friday an=
d Saturday, citing Iranian attacks on two commercial vessels in Hormuz; Iran =
retaliated against US assets in Bahrain and Kuwait; and late Sunday the two s=
ides agreed to halt attacks and resume talks, with a meeting in Doha reported=
 for Tuesday. Crude bounced about 0.9% on Monday and equity futures pointed h=
igher, leaving a market once again betting that the peace holds and that the =
Fed's harder line is more signal than action. The week ahead tests both, with=
 payrolls due into a holiday shortened week, the fragile Iran ceasefire and T=
uesday's Doha talks, Nike's print, and a dollar that has only just eased back=
 from a more than one year high.

5 Points Looking Ahead to this Week

Rates / Fed: Friday's payrolls, into a thin week. With May PCE now behind it,=
 the market's next macro test is the June employment report on Friday, due in=
to a week thinned by the 4 July holiday; the dollar has eased to about 101.3 =
on the DXY ahead of it. A firm print would harden the roughly 62% odds of a S=
eptember hike and the higher for longer message the Fed sent on 17 June, whil=
e a soft one would revive the peak dollar trade, with the two year and the te=
n year =E2=80=94 the latter back near 4.37% on the risk off bid =E2=80=94 the=
 cleanest places to watch the reaction and Fed speakers carrying extra weight=
 in a quiet, holiday week.

Commodities / geopolitics: Iran, Hormuz and Tuesday's Doha talks. Brent has f=
allen more than 40% from its April war peak to about $72 before the weekend s=
trikes nudged it back, and only a non enforced ceasefire framework is in plac=
e; Tuesday's Doha meeting between Washington and Tehran is the binary, with t=
he durability of the truce and the risk of a renewed Hormuz disruption the th=
ings to watch. A move back toward $85 in Brent would revive the very inflatio=
n question the hot PCE has just underlined, while gold near $4,067 remains th=
e cleanest hedge against the re escalation tail.

FX: the dollar, the euro and a yen in the intervention zone. The dollar sits =
just off a more than one year high, with the DXY near 101.3 and EUR/USD aroun=
d 1.141 after the ECB's 11 June move to 2.25%, leaving the Fed to ECB spread =
as the euro's swing factor; the sharper risk is in Asia, where USD/JPY holds =
about 161.7 =E2=80=94 a forty year high, the weakest yen since 1986 and squar=
ely in Ministry of Finance intervention territory =E2=80=94 so that any inter=
vention headline becomes a fast, two sided event for the yen and the wider As=
ian complex. 1.1500 in EUR/USD and the 162 area in USD/JPY are the levels to =
anchor on.

Equities / earnings: Nike, and the read through to Asia. Nike reports fiscal =
Q4 after Tuesday's close against a deliberately low bar =E2=80=94 consensus n=
ear $0.12 of EPS on about $10.85bn of revenue, roughly 3% lower year on year =
=E2=80=94 with China revenue the key tell for the broader consumer and for As=
ian demand, and options desks pricing an implied move near 8%. It lands while=
 the AI and semiconductor complex is still digesting last week's sell off, so=
 the print is as much a test of whether the tape can broaden beyond chip lead=
ership as it is a single name event.

Europe / UK: sterling at a seven month low and a softening economy. Cable has=
 slid to about 1.318, a seven month low, after a June composite PMI of 49.4 m=
arked a second straight month of UK contraction, with the Bank of England on =
hold at 3.75% and the pound caught between soft domestic data and a firm doll=
ar; on the continent, the euro area's own activity and inflation prints are w=
hat to watch for whether the soft data, firm dollar regime holds or cracks, l=
eaving both sterling and the euro hostage to the dollar's next move as much a=
s to their own data.

Bull / Base / Bear: the week ahead

Bull (~25%). June payrolls come in soft or in line rather than hot, Tuesday's=
 Doha talks hold and Hormuz stays quiet. The September hike premium fades, th=
e two year eases from its highs, the dollar gives back a little below 101, th=
e yen's intervention risk cools, and last week's equity sell off reverses int=
o a broader advance beyond the chip leadership. The most constructive of the =
three, though it leans on payrolls and geopolitics both breaking the right wa=
y at once.

Base (~50%). Payrolls print firm but not alarming and oil stays rangebound ne=
ar $72 to $80 as Hormuz headlines come and go without a real disruption. High=
er for longer holds without escalating: the front end stays anchored, the ten=
 year sits in the mid 4.30s, the dollar stays firm and USD/JPY pinned near 16=
1 to 162 under the threat of intervention, and equities steady near current l=
evels while the market waits on Nike for the next read on earnings rather tha=
n macro. A grind, not a turn.

Bear (~25%). A hot payrolls print, a collapse of the Doha framework and a ren=
ewed Hormuz closure, or some combination. September hike odds push above thei=
r current 62%, the two year and the dollar extend, the yen is forced toward a=
n intervention, and an equity tape already down about 2% on the S&P and 4.6% =
on the Nasdaq last week wobbles further as the rate relief it had been hoping=
 for is priced out. The soft UK and euro area data are the wildcard that coul=
d deepen a risk off tone rather than start one.

Focus idea of the week: a ten year range accrual

The cleaner expression of the hawkish hold view is a note linked to the ten y=
ear US Treasury yield that pays an enhanced coupon of approximately 7.5% per =
annum, net of fees, for as long as the ten year fixes inside a band of roughl=
y 4.00% to 4.90%, issued by an A rated name with capital returned at par over=
 a twelve month term; against about 4.0% on cash, the pick up is the compensa=
tion for taking the range view. With the ten year currently near 4.37%, havin=
g rallied on last week's risk off bid, the note accrues while yields hold bel=
ow 4.90%, which fits a hawkish hold that keeps rates elevated without breakin=
g sharply higher, and this week's payrolls are the catalyst =E2=80=94 a firm =
but not runaway print keeps the ten year comfortably inside the band and the =
coupon accruing. Two risks are worth naming: the ten year rising above 4.90% =
on a very hot print, which breaches the range and costs accrual; and call or =
reinvestment risk, since a fall in yields after the first year could let the =
issuer call the note early and leave the investor reinvesting at lower rates.

As of 29 June 2026 (week ending 26 June 2026). Sources (each fact verified by=
 at least two): Reuters, WSJ, Bloomberg, Yahoo Finance, Seeking Alpha, Barron=
's.

Flagged as pending/developing: the Iran ceasefire and Tuesday's Doha talks ar=
e fast moving and the framework is not enforced; Friday's payrolls and Nike's=
 fiscal Q4 are upcoming events; implied moves are options desk estimates. For=
 discussion only =E2=80=94 not an offer, a recommendation, investment researc=
h, or personalised investment advice.

